1
00:00:00,500 --> 00:00:04,500
Claude Code is powerful out of the box...
But every session starts fresh.

2
00:00:04,500 --> 00:00:08,000
It doesn't remember your team's rules.
Your project's architecture.

3
00:00:08,000 --> 00:00:12,000
Or the mistakes it made yesterday...
ClaudeOS fixes that.

4
00:00:13,500 --> 00:00:18,000
Four files load into every session...
automatically.

5
00:00:18,000 --> 00:00:22,500
Your team's build commands and architecture.
Your personal review style and preferences.

6
00:00:22,500 --> 00:00:27,000
Permission auto-approvals, so Claude
doesn't ask for confirmation on safe commands.

7
00:00:27,000 --> 00:00:31,500
And a living memory... of patterns
learned across hundreds of sessions.

8
00:00:31,500 --> 00:00:37,500
Plus twenty-two topic files,
auto-synced from Confluence every twenty-four hours.

9
00:00:38,800 --> 00:00:43,000
Claude learns from its mistakes.
When it tries to use the gh CLI...

10
00:00:43,000 --> 00:00:47,500
which isn't installed... that gets logged.
After multiple occurrences across sessions,

11
00:00:47,500 --> 00:00:52,000
the pattern gets recognized...
and promoted to a permanent rule.

12
00:00:52,000 --> 00:00:56,000
From that point on...
Claude never makes that mistake again.

13
00:00:56,000 --> 00:01:00,500
The progression is... session log,
to recognized pattern, to permanent rule.

14
00:01:01,800 --> 00:01:05,500
Five scheduled scripts
replace the manual loop.

15
00:01:05,500 --> 00:01:09,000
Logging every hour. Distilling patterns daily.
Promoting rules weekly.

16
00:01:09,000 --> 00:01:13,000
Syncing Confluence and Notion docs...
automatically.

17
00:01:13,000 --> 00:01:17,000
All running on launchd, across two repos.
Ten agents total.

18
00:01:18,300 --> 00:01:22,500
Custom slash commands turn
multi-step workflows... into one-liners.

19
00:01:22,500 --> 00:01:26,500
Type slash review with a ticket number...
and Claude fetches the branch,

20
00:01:26,500 --> 00:01:30,500
diffs every file, runs regression scans,
and posts a categorized review...

21
00:01:30,500 --> 00:01:35,000
directly on the pull request.
Here's a real review it posted on Bitbucket.

22
00:01:36,300 --> 00:01:40,000
Setting up a new repo...
takes one command.

23
00:01:40,000 --> 00:01:44,000
Bootstrap copies your templates,
slash commands, automation scripts, and starter memory.

24
00:01:44,000 --> 00:01:48,500
Checkpoint saves changes back.
Your conventions... travel with you...

25
00:01:48,500 --> 00:01:50,500
across every project.

26
00:01:51,500 --> 00:01:54,500
All of this... runs for about
four dollars a week.

27
00:01:54,500 --> 00:01:56,800
Each script is budget-capped.
No surprises.
